<item>
            <title>[LU-13005] Remove LNet event queuing subsystem (lib-eq)</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-13005</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;lib-eq provides a &quot;event queue&apos; which allows one thread to add events to a queue, and another to remove them, or wait for more.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Such a&#160; queue would be useful if LNet were accessed from user-space: allowing user-space to pluck events of a queue with minimal interaction with the kernel would be valuable.&#160; But lnet/eq is never used like that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Almost all users for LNet/eq allocate a queue with zero slots and provide a call-back to be called for each event.&#160; This is a sensible approach when producer and consumer are in the same address space (i.e. both in the kernel).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The one exception is lnet_ping() which allocated a 2-element queue.&#160; lnet_ping() can easily be re-written to use a call-back, with a reduction in code size.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So let&apos;s remove the whole EQ subsystem and just use callbacks everywhere.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
